Day 74 Summary â€“ CompTIA Security+

Focus: Security Architecture (Practice Quiz â€“ 20 Questions)

Core Topics Covered

Power & Availability

UPS (Uninterruptible Power Supply): Provides short-term backup power during outages or fluctuations, allowing systems to shut down gracefully and preventing data loss.

Elasticity: The ability of systems (especially cloud environments) to automatically scale resources up or down based on demand.

Network Access & Segmentation

Jump Servers: Act as controlled connection points between security zones. They are highly restricted, logged, and isolated to prevent unauthorized lateral movement.

Security Zones: Logical or physical network separations that limit access and contain threats within defined boundaries.

Air Gaps: Physical isolation of a network segment with no logical or physical connection to external systems, preventing remote access entirely.

Unified & Layered Security

UTM (Unified Threat Management): Combines multiple security functions (firewall, IDS/IPS, VPN, DLP, etc.) into a single centralized interface for simplified management and visibility.

Appropriate Data Security by State:

Data in Transit: Encryption (VPN, TLS/IPSec), integrity checks

Data in Use: Strong access controls, role-based permissions

Data at Rest: Encryption, physical security, strict access policies

Network Architecture Models

Decentralized Architecture: Distributes infrastructure across multiple locations (e.g., cloud or hybrid environments) to improve resilience.

Centralized Architecture: Concentrates network infrastructure in a single primary location (on-prem or data center).

Architecture vs Infrastructure:

Architecture = how the network is designed and organized

Infrastructure = the hardware/software components that implement that design

Operational & Specialized Systems

RTOS (Real-Time Operating Systems): Used in environments requiring immediate response (medical devices, industrial systems). Prioritizes deterministic timing over throughput.

Pacemaker Example: RTOS can detect abnormal heart rhythms and immediately alert or respond without delay.

Failure Behavior & Networking Standards

Fail-Open vs Fail-Closed:

Fail-Open: Allows traffic when a system fails (availability prioritized)

Fail-Closed: Blocks traffic when a system fails (security prioritized)

IEEE: Organization responsible for networking standards such as 802.1X, used for wired and wireless network authentication.

VPN Configurations

Full Tunnel VPN: Routes all traffic through the VPN.

Split Tunnel VPN: Routes only specific traffic through the VPN, allowing other traffic to bypass it.

Resilience & Recovery

Failover: Automatically shifts operations from a primary system to a backup system. Highly intrusive but provides the most accurate validation of resilience and recovery performance.

ðŸ“Œ Key Takeaways

Strong security architecture balances availability, segmentation, and control.

Isolation techniques (jump servers, zones, air gaps) significantly reduce attack surface.

Understanding failure behavior (fail-open vs fail-closed) is critical for real-world decision-making.

RTOS and specialized systems emphasize speed and determinism over flexibility.

This quiz showed improved performance and confidence in architecture concepts.
